            "id": "49b1e4c61cd343c1b90b1",
            "questionText": "A scuba diver takes a breath of air at the surface of the ocean. At the surface, the pressure is $!$1 \\text{ atm}$!$, the temperature is $!$298 \\text{ K}$!$, and the volume of air in the diver's lungs is $!$6 \\text{ liters}$!$. The diver then descends to a depth where the pressure is $!$2.5 \\text{ atm}$!$ and the temperature is $!$288 \\text{ K}$!$. Assuming the amount of air remains constant, calculate the new volume of air in the diver's lungs at this depth, assuming they held their breath.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "028f0b7838ad4edfa2a12",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling the correct relationship that applies for a fixed amount of gas where pressure, volume, and temperature are involved. Identify which of the following formulas correctly represents this constant relationship.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0d435e5c-9b10-457d-a7e6-d3de648690e5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$ \\frac{P_1V_1}{T_1} = \\frac{P_2V_2}{T_2} $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$ P_1V_1 = P_2V_2 $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$ \\frac{V_1}{T_1} = \\frac{V_2}{T_2} $!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e00ea04ba4e648a59a22e",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that we've identified the proper relationship, let\u2019s calculate the pressure ratio $!$ (P_1/P_2) $!$. Use the given pressures $!$P_1 = 1\\,atm$!$ and $!$P_2 = 2.5\\,atm$!$ to compute this ratio.",
