        {
            "id": "03bd8d396cc04870a90a3",
            "questionText": "A sealed bag of chips is transported from sea level to a mountain summit. At sea level, the bag contains air at a pressure of $!$1 \\text{ atm}$!$ and a temperature of $!$293 \\text{ K}$!$. Upon reaching the summit, the atmospheric pressure drops to $!$0.7 \\text{ atm}$!$ and the temperature decreases to $!$273 \\text{ K}$!$. Assuming the bag can freely expand, calculate the percentage change in the volume of the bag.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "75c7414cd9f04290b45aa",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by recalling the fundamental gas law that relates pressure, volume, number of moles, temperature, and the gas constant. Please select the correct formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0d435e5c-9b10-457d-a7e6-d3de648690e5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$PV = nRT$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = nRT$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V = nRT$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "8f5718d6e94846779be85",
                    "stepText": "Given that the number of moles remains constant, the volume is proportional to the temperature divided by the pressure. Which of the following correctly represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0d435e5c-9b10-457d-a7e6-d3de648690e5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V \\propto \\frac{T}{P}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V \\propto T \\cdot P$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V \\propto \\frac{P}{T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "cc158863e14441ccb337d",
                    "stepText": "Great, now calculate the ratio $!$T_1/P_1$!$ using the sea level values: $!$T_1 = 293 \\text{ K}$!$ and $!$P_1 = 1 \\text{ atm}$!$. What is this ratio?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "293"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K/atm",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0d435e5c-9b10-457d-a7e6-d3de648690e5"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ce4fb955327c4c208c878",
                    "stepText": "Next, compute the ratio $!$T_2/P_2$!$ using the summit conditions: $!$T_2 = 273 \\text{ K}$!$ and $!$P_2 = 0.7 \\text{ atm}$!$. What value do you get?",
                    "stepText2": "",
